item.title: adductor brevis
item.description:
#addDetail
little blurb #addDetail
Origin
The body of the pubis and the inferior pubic rami.
Body
This muscles runs deep to the pectineus and the adductor longus.
Insertion
The linea aspera on the posterior surface of the femur.
Innervation
Tibial nerve (S2-S3)
Action
Hip adduction and flexion. It may also act as an internal or external rotator depending on the position of the femur relative to the hip. It also assists in balancing the pelvis in closed chain activation while standing and walking.

item.title: adductor magnus
item.description:
The adductor magnus is a large triangular muscle originating from the pelvis and inserting all along the length of the femur. It is situated in both the medial and posterior compartments of the thigh but is largely classified as part of the medial compartment. It is the strongest muscle within this compartment and participates in adduction, flexion, extension, internal/external rotation and femoropelvic stabilization.
Origin
The adductor (pubofemoral) portion of the muscle originates on the inferior ramus of the pubis and ramus of the ischium.
The hamstring (ischiocondylar) portion of the muscles originates from the ischial tuberosity.
Body
The body of the adductor magnus fans out from the ischium/pubis and to reach along the femur.
There are four small arches/openings formed by tendinous connective tissue near where the adductor magnus inserts, and the lowest/most caudal is the adductor hiatus.
Insertion
The adductor part inserts in to the posterior surface of the proximal femur, fans down along the middle of the linea aspera, and at its most inferior into the medial supracondylar line. Its distal attachment on the linea aspera has it blend with the fibers of the short head of the biceps femoris.
The hamstring part inserts into the adductor tubercle of the medial condyle of the femur and the supracondylar line
Action
Its most basic function is to adduct and internally rotate the femur. As well, its anterior and posterior fibers may assist in flexion and extension of the femur respectively. It is a very effective hip extensor when the hip is flexed.
It is also an effective dynamic stabilizer of the femur on the hip socket.
Innervation
Adductor part: obturator nerve (L2-L4)
Hamstring part: tibial portion of the sciatic nerve (L4)

item.title: adductor minimus
item.description:
The adductor minimus comprise the the proximal lateral part of the adductor magnus. This muscle is variably fused to the upper border of the adductor magnus and is thus sometimes not considered to be a separate muscle.
see adductor magnus
Origin
The inferior ramus of the pubis
Body
Runs laterally just inferior to the quadratus femoris
Insertion
The medial lip of the proximal linea aspera
Innervation
Obturator nerve (L2-L4), tibial portion of the sciatic nerve (L4)
Action
Adduction, extension, and external rotation of the femur.

item.title: Deep Front Line
item.description:
#addDetail #maybe
Static Function

lifting inner arch
stabilizing legs
supporting lumbar spine
supporting abdominal viscera
stabilizing chest during movement of ribcage with breath
balancing neck and head
Dynamic Function
The DFL does not have a specific movement function in the body, but its proper function allows all other fascial lines within the body to work with more grace and efficiency. The flip-side to this is that any disfunction in the DFL manifests elsewhere in the body as well and will create compensatory habits that can eventually lead to pain and discomfort in even day to day function.
Trace
We trace from bottom to top the entire line from its most inferior to most superior bony attachments. This line is unique given that it also engulfs much of the bodies viscera and has multiple sub paths to trace. Thus we organize the line into 6 subsections which encapsulate its functions.
The Lowest Common Track

Plantar aspect of the tarsals
Tibialis posterior, flexor hallucis longus, flexor digitorum longus
Posterosuperior tibia/fibula
Popliteus, Popliteal fascia
Medial femoral epicondyle
The muscles of this track are partially responsible for flexion of the toes and plantar flexion of the ankle, as well as supporting the medial arch of the foot. Dysfunction in this portion of the DFL typically results in both high and fallen arch patterns, and hallux varus and valgus.
The major fascial walls surrounding the adductors of the femur split sagittally, so we term the continuities of the DFL the Lower Anterior and Posterior Tracks of the DFL.
Lower Posterior Track

Medial femoral epicondyle
Posterior intermuscular septum, adductor magnus and adductor minimus
Ischial ramus
Pelvic floor fascia, pelvic floor , obturator internus fascia
Coccyx
Anterior sacral fascia, anterior longitudinal ligament
Lumbar vertebral bodies
Lower Anterior

Medial femoral epicondyle
Linea aspera of the femur
Medial intermuscular septum, adductor brevis, adductor longus
Lesser trochanter of the femur
psoas, iliacus, pectineus, femoral triangle
Lumbar vertebral bodies and transverse processes
Upper Posterior Track

Lumbar vertebral bodies
Anterior longitudinal ligament, longus colli, longus capitis
Basilar portion of occiput
Upper Middle

Lumbar vertebral bodies
Posterior diaphragm, crura of diaphragm, central tendon
pericardium, mediastinum, parietal pleura
Fascia prevertebralis, pharyngeal raphe, scalene muscles, medial scalene fascia
Basilar portion of occiput, cervical transverse processes
Upper Anterior

Lumbar vertebral bodies
Anterior diaphragm
Posterior surface of subcostal, cartilages, xiphoid process
Fascia endothoracica, transversus thoracis
Posterior manubrium of sternum
Infrahyoid muscles, fascia pretrachialis
Hyoid bone
Suprahyoid muscles
Mandible

item.title: diaphragm
item.description:
The diaphragm is a major anatomical landmark that separates the thorax from the abdomen. It is a fibromuscular sheet that has a convex upper surface to form this delineation.
It has four major functions
Inspiration
During contraction the diaphragm increases the vertical diameter of the thorax . This decreases pressure within the thoracic cavity in order to draw in air. In expiration the diaphragm relaxes and elevates, creating the opposite effect in order to push air out of the body.
Abdominal Straining
The contraction of the diaphragm increases intra-abdominal pressure which aids in processes like urination, defecation, and child birth.
Abdominal Stability
The increase of intra-abdominal pressure during contraction of the diaphragm also increases the general stability of the trunk by minimizing displacements of abdominal contents, assisting the muscles of the anterior abdominal wall, and increasing tension in the thoracolumbar fascia thus stabilizing the spine.
Fluid Flow
The decrease in intrathoracic pressure during inspiration compresses the blood in the inferior vena cava to force it into the right atrium to fill the heart. This negative pressure also assists abdominal lymph vessels in upward flow.
Origin
The origin of the fibers of the diaphragm can be divided into three separate origin points

The sternal part originates from the posterior aspect of the xiphoid process.
The costal part originates from from the inner surface of the seventh to twelfth costal cartilages and adjacent parts of the corresponding ribs.
The lumbar part originates from the medial and lateral arcuate ligaments and from the first to third lumbar vertebrae.

item.title: flexor digitorum longus
item.description:
#addDetail
little blurb #addDetail
Origin
Th medial portion of the posterior tibia. Just inferior to the soleal line of the the tibia.
Body
The muscle runs down through the posterior compartment of the leg, and passes posterior to the medial malleolus and deep to the flexor retinaculum. It then passes into the plantar compartment of the foot where it splits into four separate tendons.
Insertion
The base of the distal phalanges of the lateral four digits of the foot.
Innervation
Tibial nerve (S2-S3)
Action
Primarily flexes the lateral four digits of the foot at both interphalangeal joints and the metatarsophalangeal joint. Aids in plantarflexion of the ankle.

item.title: flexor hallucis longus
item.description:
#addDetail
little blurb #addDetail
Origin
Lower two-thirds of the posterior aspect of the fibula.
Body
It passes downward, profound to the flexor retinaculum. It wraps around the distal end of the tibia, the back of the talus, and then enters the sole of the foot, entering the fibrous sheath of the big toe, passing between the two sesamoid bones.
Insertion
The base of the distal phalanx of the big toe.
Innervation
A branch of the tibial nerve (S1-S2)
Cutaneous supply from root S2
Action
Primarily acts as a flexor of the big toe. Stabilizes the first metatarsal and provides the final push from the foot in the toe-off phase of the gait. Contributes to maintaining the medial longitudinal arch. Aids in plantarflexion at the ankle joint.

item.title: Iliococcygeus
item.description:
#addDetail
little blurb #addDetail
Origin
The ischial spine and posterior tendinous arch of the internal obturator fascia.
Body
It runs along the length of the pelvic floor forming a the middle portion of the pelvic bowl.
Insertion
Into the anococcygeal ligament, perineal body, the coccyx, and into the musculature of the prostate/vagina.
Innervation
The nerve to levator ani and branches of the Pudenal nerve (S2-S4)
Action
Stabilization of the abdominal and pelvic organs and control of the opening/closing of the levator hiatus.

item.title: pelvic floor
item.description: The pelvic floor or pelvic diaphragm is the name given to the group of muscles which make up the base of the pelvic cavity and support the abdominal viscera. These muscles stretch from the pubis to the coccyx and form a sling around the rectum and genitals and work to tighten or relax the urogenital and rectal hiatuses. The broad name for this stretch of these muscles is the levator ani given its function in tightening and elevating the anal opening but is made up of a group of muscles.

item.title: Popliteus
item.description:
#addDetail
little blurb #addDetail
Origin
Lateral condyle of the femur.
Body
It runs directly inferior and medial from its origin point, forming the base of the popliteal fossa.
Insertion
Posterior surface of the proximal tibia, superior to the soleal line. It also has attachments to the lateral meniscus via aponeurosis.
Innervation
Tibial Nerve (L5-S1)
Action
The muscle is a major stabilizer of the knee and has different functions depending on whether the leg is weight bearing or not. When the leg is lifted off of the ground the popliteus is an internal rotator of the tibia in relation to the femur. When the leg is weight bearing the popliteus acts as an external rotator of the femur in relation to the tibia, preventing the "locked" state of the knee.

item.title: Pubococcygeus
item.description:
#addDetail
little blurb #addDetail
Origin
The posterior surface of the pubic bones, just lateral to the puborectalis.
Body
It runs along the length of the pelvic floor forming a U shape around the puborectalis.
Insertion
Into the anococcygeal ligament, the coccyx, and into the musculature of the prostate/vagina.
Innervation
The nerve to levator ani and branches of the Pudenal nerve (S2-S4)
Action
Stabilization of the abdominal and pelvic organs and control of the opening/closing of the levator hiatus.

item.title: Puborectalis
item.description:
#addDetail
little blurb #addDetail
Origin
Posterior surface of bodies of pubic bones, lateral from the pubic symphysis of both sides.
Body
Encircles the rectum and causes an anterior bend between the rectum and anal canal.
Insertion
None, it forms a U-shaped sling around and behind the rectum just superior to the external sphincter.
Innervation
S4
Action
Through general tonic activity it stabilizes the abdominal and pelvic organs and controls the opening and closing of the levator hiatus.

item.title: Tibialis posterior
item.description:
The tibialis posterior is in the deep posterior compartment of the leg and is a key stabilizer of the medial longitudinal arch of the foot
Origin
Proximal posterolateral aspect of the tibia
Proximal posteromedial aspect of the fibula
Interosseous membrane
Body
Deep posterior compartment of the lower leg. Runs proximal to the medial malleolus, secured by the flexor retinaculum.
Insertion
Majorly onto the navicular
Partially onto the medial cuneiform
Innervation
Tibial Nerve, a branch of the sciatic nerve
Action
Plantarflex and invert the ankle
Stabilizing the medial longitudinal arch
